---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
const pdfHref = base + '/assets/docs/ResumeChen230423.pdf';
---

<Layout title="Resume — EE Heng Chen">
  <PageHeader title="Resume" subtitle="The short version." volume="05" />

  <section class="space-y-6 leading-relaxed text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-200">
    <p>
      The resume layouts nowadays are getting really creative — sometimes too creative.
      I like the layouts with a sidebar listing the author's information. But the layouts
      that rate skills with bars or stars are, in my opinion, not very informative.
      Is it for faster visual comprehension? If so, what stops the author from just
      putting full stars?
    </p>

    <p>
      In the meantime, here is my old-school resume:
      <a class="underline font-medium" href={pdfHref} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Resume (PDF) →
      </a>
    </p>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight mt-4 mb-3">In a nutshell</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
        <li>~5 years of experience working in industry as a student and as a PhD candidate.</li>
        <li>
          7 years of computer-vision research experience. Worked with KinectV1 and
          Realsense RGB-D cameras; used mainly OpenCV, TensorFlow, and PyTorch.
        </li>
        <li>Comfortable reading and debugging Python and C++.</li>
        <li>
          Experience with Kubernetes and Docker — enough to start on real tasks, and
          I genuinely enjoy this side of the work.
        </li>
        <li>Experience coordinating interdisciplinary projects.</li>
        <li>Experience supervising student work.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
